answers.body_markdown:
There is no corresponding object literal syntax to define  an object literal with `new`. You can use a class expression:

```ts
const k = class {
  constructor () {
    
  }
}

new k()
```
[play](https://www.typescriptlang.org/play/#code/MYewdgzgLgBA1jAvDYAbAhhCMDeBYAKBhXGgCcBXYKEMmACgEpdDjjWYBfQ7gwsAKYB3eEyA)

The keyword `new` is used to **instantiate** a class. 

```typescript
const k = new MyClass();
```

To define the constructor of this class you have to use the `constructor` keyword.

```typescript

class MyClass1 {
  constructor() {
  }
}

const MyClass2 = class {
  constructor() {
  }
}

interface MyClass3 {
    constructor(): Function;  // should be Function *if* we want it generic
}
```

`MyClass1` and `MyClass2` are quite equivalent. 

Be careful to `MyClass3`, you can&#39;t do something like `const k = new MyClass3()`. But you can do `const k: MyClass3 = new MyClass1()`. `MyClass3` is an interface, so you can use it only for typing nothing more.

Note that in Typescript when you define a class, it&#39;s also creating an interface. It&#39;s why a class can `implements` another class.

More info with TS doc:
[Class][1]
[Interface][2]


  [1]: https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/classes.html
  [2]: https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/interfaces.html

